-- COMPLIANCE & REGULATIONS
INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('HIPAA', 'Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act - federal law protecting patient health information privacy and security.', 'HIPAA (enacted 1996) establishes national standards for protecting patient Protected Health Information (PHI). Key components include: Privacy Rule (controls use and disclosure of PHI), Security Rule (protects electronic PHI with administrative, physical, and technical safeguards), Breach Notification Rule (requires notification of data breaches), and Enforcement Rule (outlines penalties for violations). HIPAA applies to covered entities (healthcare providers, health plans, clearinghouses) and business associates (vendors handling PHI). Violations range from $100 to $50,000 per violation, with annual maximums up to $1.5 million per violation category. Compliance requires: written policies and procedures, staff training, risk assessments, business associate agreements, and breach response plans.', 'A medical practice implements HIPAA compliance: (1) All staff complete annual HIPAA training, (2) Computer systems require unique user IDs and complex passwords, (3) Paper records are locked, (4) Business associate agreements are signed with billing company and IT vendor, (5) Encryption is used for all electronic PHI, (6) A privacy officer is designated, (7) Patients sign HIPAA authorization forms before information is shared.', 'HIPAA violations can result in massive fines, criminal charges, loss of medical license, reputation damage, and civil lawsuits. OCR (Office for Civil Rights) actively investigates complaints and conducts audits. Breaches affecting 500+ individuals must be publicly reported. Proper HIPAA compliance protects patients, providers, and practices. Cybersecurity measures protecting PHI are a HIPAA requirement, not optional.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['PHI', 'Privacy Rule', 'Security Rule', 'Business Associate Agreement']),

('Compliance', 'Adhering to laws, regulations, and ethical standards in healthcare billing and coding practices.', 'Healthcare compliance encompasses federal and state laws, payer contracts, professional standards, and internal policies. Key areas include: accurate coding and billing (avoiding fraud and abuse), HIPAA privacy and security, Stark Law and Anti-Kickback Statute, False Claims Act, medical necessity requirements, documentation standards, and proper use of modifiers. Compliance programs include: written policies, regular auditing and monitoring, staff training, response and corrective action plans, and designated compliance officers. OIG (Office of Inspector General) provides compliance guidance for various healthcare sectors. Non-compliance risks include: audits, repayment demands, civil monetary penalties, exclusion from federal programs, and criminal prosecution.', 'A practice establishes a compliance program: (1) Appoints a compliance officer, (2) Creates written policies on proper coding, documentation, and billing, (3) Conducts quarterly internal audits of 10 charts per provider, (4) Provides annual compliance training to all staff, (5) Establishes anonymous reporting mechanisms for potential violations, (6) Responds to compliance issues with corrective action plans and overpayment returns when appropriate.', 'Healthcare compliance prevents fraud allegations, audit findings, and penalties that can devastate practices. The False Claims Act allows whistleblowers to file qui tam lawsuits, and providers can be liable for triple damages plus penalties. Proactive compliance programs demonstrate good faith efforts and can reduce penalties if violations occur. Regular internal audits identify and correct issues before external audits find them.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['HIPAA', 'Medical Necessity', 'Fraud and Abuse', 'False Claims Act']),

('Medical Necessity', 'The requirement that healthcare services must be appropriate, reasonable, and necessary for diagnosis or treatment.', 'Medical necessity is determined by: clinical standards of care, FDA-approved uses, published medical literature, and payer medical policies. Services that are not medically necessary are not covered by insurance, even if they are provided. Documentation must support medical necessity - the diagnosis codes must support the procedure codes billed. Payers define medical necessity through: national coverage determinations (NCDs), local coverage determinations (LCDs), and medical policies. Services performed without establishing medical necessity may be denied, and providers may not be able to bill patients for these services. Medical necessity is the most common reason for claim denials requiring appeals.', 'A patient requests an MRI for chronic back pain. The physician''s documentation shows: 8 weeks of conservative treatment (physical therapy, medications), persistent symptoms, neurological deficits on exam, and need to rule out disc herniation before considering surgery. This documentation establishes medical necessity. Without documenting failed conservative treatment and specific clinical findings, the MRI might be denied as not medically necessary.', 'Lack of medical necessity is a primary reason for claim denials and audit findings. Providers must understand payer medical policies before ordering services. Documentation must paint a clear picture of why services are necessary. Services provided without medical necessity may need to be refunded if already paid. Prior authorization processes are designed to pre-determine medical necessity before services are rendered.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['ICD-10 Code', 'Authorization', 'Coverage Determination', 'Clinical Documentation']),

('Stark Law', 'Federal law prohibiting physician self-referral to entities with which they have financial relationships.', 'The Physician Self-Referral Law (Stark Law) prohibits physicians from referring Medicare/Medicaid patients for designated health services (DHS) to entities with which they have financial relationships, unless an exception applies. DHS includes: lab services, imaging, physical therapy, DME, inpatient/outpatient hospital services, and more. Financial relationships include ownership, investment interests, and compensation arrangements. Violations are strict liability (intent not required) and can result in: denial of payment, refund of amounts collected, civil monetary penalties up to $25,000 per violation, and exclusion from federal programs. Unlike fraud statutes, Stark violations don''t require intent. Numerous exceptions exist (in-office ancillary services, fair market value compensation, etc.) but must be strictly followed.', 'A physician owns 20% of an imaging center. Under Stark Law, they cannot refer their Medicare patients to that imaging center unless a specific exception applies. If the imaging center performs only in-office services ancillary to the physician''s practice and meets all requirements of the in-office ancillary services exception, referrals may be permitted. The arrangement must be carefully structured and documented.', 'Stark Law violations, even unintentional, can result in massive financial penalties and exclusion from Medicare. Many practices unknowingly violate Stark through poorly structured arrangements with providers or entities. Legal counsel should review all financial relationships with referral sources or referral targets. Self-disclosure of violations through the Self-Referral Disclosure Protocol (SRDP) can reduce penalties.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Anti-Kickback Statute', 'Compliance', 'Fraud and Abuse', 'Designated Health Services']),

('Anti-Kickback Statute (AKS)', 'Federal criminal law prohibiting offering, paying, soliciting, or receiving remuneration to induce referrals of federal healthcare program business.', 'The Anti-Kickback Statute (AKS) prohibits knowingly and willfully offering, paying, soliciting, or receiving anything of value to induce or reward referrals or generate federal healthcare program business. Unlike Stark, AKS requires intent, applies to all items/services (not just DHS), covers both federal and private payers in some states, and is a criminal statute (not just civil). Violations can result in: criminal penalties (up to 5 years in prison, $25,000 fines per violation), civil monetary penalties ($50,000+ per violation plus treble damages), and exclusion from federal programs. Safe harbors provide protection if all requirements are met. Common risk areas: free or below-market leases, forgiveness of patient cost-sharing, excessive compensation for services, and gifts to referral sources.', 'A physician group enters a management services agreement with a hospital. To comply with AKS safe harbors, the agreement must: be in writing and signed, specify all services to be provided, set compensation at fair market value, cover at least one year, and not be based on volume or value of referrals. If the hospital pays above-market rates or includes bonuses tied to referrals, this could violate AKS.', 'AKS violations carry serious criminal liability, unlike purely civil violations. Prosecutors increasingly pursue AKS cases, especially those involving patient harm or large amounts. The False Claims Act can be implicated by AKS violations, creating both criminal and civil liability. Many states have their own kickback laws applying to private payers. All referral relationships, employment agreements, and financial arrangements should be reviewed by healthcare counsel.', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Stark Law', 'Fraud and Abuse', 'Compliance', 'Safe Harbor']);

-- CLAIMS & DENIALS (additional terms)
INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('Claim Denial', 'An insurance payer''s refusal to pay for a submitted claim, either partially or in full.', 'Denials occur when claims do not meet payer requirements for payment. Denials are different from rejections - rejections occur before claim adjudication due to technical errors, while denials occur after adjudication. Common denial reasons: missing or invalid information (patient demographics, insurance info), lack of medical necessity, services not covered, authorization not obtained, timely filing limits exceeded, duplicate claims, coding errors, and eligibility issues. Denial codes (CARC and RARC) explain the reason. Some denials are "soft" (correctable and resubmittable) while others are "hard" (require appeal). Industry averages show 5-10% denial rates, but this varies by specialty and payer. Prevention is more cost-effective than denial rework.', 'A surgery claim is denied with code CO-16: "Claim/service lacks information which is needed for adjudication." Review reveals the diagnosis code was missing. This is a soft denial - the claim can be corrected with the diagnosis code and resubmitted for payment. The same claim denied with code CO-50 for "not covered" would require an appeal with medical records to demonstrate coverage.', 'Every denied claim represents delayed or lost revenue and increases administrative costs. The average cost to work a denial is $25-$50, making denial prevention crucial. High denial rates indicate systemic revenue cycle problems. First-pass resolution rate (percentage of claims paid on first submission) is a key performance indicator. Reducing denials by just 2-3% can add hundreds of thousands to practice revenue annually.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['Denial Management', 'Claim Rejection', 'Appeal Process', 'Denial Codes']),

('Claim Rejection', 'A claim returned by a payer before processing due to technical errors or missing required information.', 'Rejections differ from denials - rejections occur at the clearinghouse or payer front-end before adjudication, typically within hours or days. Common rejection reasons: invalid patient or subscriber ID, invalid payer ID, invalid provider NPI, duplicate claim, invalid CPT or diagnosis codes, missing required information, and formatting errors. Rejections must be corrected and resubmitted; they do not count against timely filing limits. Modern claim scrubbing software catches most rejections before submission. Clearinghouses provide rejection reports identifying specific errors. High rejection rates indicate data quality issues or system problems requiring correction.', 'A practice submits 100 claims to Medicare. Five are rejected by the clearinghouse with the error: "Invalid Medicare ID number - check digit does not match." The billing staff corrects the Medicare ID numbers, resubmits the claims the same day, and they pass clearinghouse edits and are sent to Medicare for processing. No time is lost since rejections don''t count toward timely filing.', 'While rejections are less serious than denials (they can be quickly corrected and resubmitted), high rejection rates indicate poor data quality and increase workload. Best practices target rejection rates below 2-3%. Real-time eligibility verification at registration prevents many rejection reasons. Claim scrubbing before submission catches most errors. Staff training on proper data entry (especially insurance information) reduces rejections.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['Claim Denial', 'Clean Claim', 'Claim Scrubbing', 'Clearinghouse']),

('Appeal Process', 'The formal procedure for challenging an insurance company''s claim denial or payment decision.', 'When a claim is denied, providers have the right to appeal through a structured process. Most payers have multiple appeal levels: first-level (reconsideration), second-level (independent review), and final (external review or payer board). Appeals must be filed within specific timeframes (typically 30-180 days depending on payer and claim type). Successful appeals require: clear written explanation of why the denial is incorrect, supporting documentation (medical records, payer policies, medical literature), and specific reference to coverage policies. Appeals should be tracked with deadlines monitored. For Medicare, appeals progress through: redetermination, reconsideration, ALJ hearing, Medicare Appeals Council, and federal court. Success rates vary, but 40-60% of appealed denials are overturned.', 'A surgery claim is denied for lack of medical necessity. The surgeon files a first-level appeal within 30 days, including: detailed operative report, office notes showing failed conservative treatment, peer-reviewed studies supporting the procedure, and citation of the payer''s medical policy with explanation of how the case meets criteria. The appeal is successful, and the $15,000 claim is paid 45 days after the appeal.', 'Appeals can recover significant denied revenue - often tens of thousands per month for busy practices. However, appeals are time-consuming, so prioritization is essential (focus on high-dollar, clinically appropriate denials). Tracking appeal success rates by denial reason and payer identifies which denials are worth appealing. Pattern recognition from appeals can identify root causes to prevent future denials. External review rights exist if internal appeals are exhausted.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['Denial Management', 'Medical Necessity', 'Peer Review', 'Overturn Rate']),

('Timely Filing', 'The deadline within which insurance claims must be submitted to payers for payment consideration.', 'Timely filing limits vary by payer and contract, typically ranging from 90 days to one year from the date of service. Commercial payers often have 90-180 day limits, while Medicare has a one-year timely filing limit. Claims submitted after the deadline are denied as untimely and cannot be collected from the patient (due to contract requirements). Timely filing denials are considered "hard denials" with very limited appeal rights. Exceptions may exist for: corrected claims (resubmissions after denials), retroactive eligibility determinations, or payer processing delays. Best practices include submitting clean claims within 24-48 hours of service and tracking all denials to ensure resubmissions stay within timely filing.', 'A practice submits a claim 95 days after the date of service. The payer contract specifies a 90-day timely filing limit. The claim is denied as untimely filing, and the practice cannot collect the $800 from the patient due to contractual obligations. If the claim had been initially submitted within 90 days but denied for a correctable reason, the corrected resubmission would typically be allowed even after the initial filing deadline.', 'Timely filing denials represent completely unrecoverable revenue losses. Missing timely filing due to process delays, claim backlogs, or overlooked denials directly impacts bottom-line profitability. Practices should submit all claims within days of service, not weeks or months. Automated claim submission processes prevent filing delays. Tracking initial denial dates and calculating remaining filing time prevents secondary losses when reworking denied claims.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['Clean Claim', 'Denial Management', 'Claim Submission', 'Hard Denial']),

('Claim Scrubbing', 'The automated process of reviewing claims for errors before submission to payers.', 'Claim scrubbing software checks claims against payer rules, coding guidelines, and common rejection reasons before submission. Scrubbing identifies: invalid or outdated codes, missing required information, incorrect modifier usage, coding logic errors, gender/age conflicts, medical necessity issues, and authorization requirement alerts. Scrubbing occurs at multiple levels: practice management system edits, clearinghouse scrubbing, and specialized third-party scrubbing services. Effective scrubbing can reduce rejections and denials by 30-50%. Scrubbing rules must be continuously updated as payer requirements and code sets change. While automated, scrubbing results require human review to override false positives and address complex situations.', 'A practice submits claims through a clearinghouse with advanced scrubbing. A claim for a knee MRI is flagged because: (1) the procedure code requires a "LT" or "RT" modifier for laterality, (2) the diagnosis code suggests an upper extremity problem rather than knee, and (3) the scrubber identifies that this payer requires prior authorization for MRI. The billing staff corrects the missing modifier, reviews the diagnosis code with the provider, and verifies the authorization before resubmitting.', 'Claim scrubbing is a cost-effective way to improve clean claim rates and reduce denials. Every claim error caught before submission prevents a rejection or denial that would cost $25-$50 in rework time. Scrubbing also provides staff education - seeing common errors helps billers learn correct practices. However, scrubbing is not a substitute for accurate initial data entry and coding. Over-reliance on scrubbing can mask underlying quality issues that should be addressed through training.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['Clean Claim', 'Claim Rejection', 'Clearinghouse', 'Edit Checks']);

