INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('Electronic Health Record (EHR)', 'A digital version of a patient''s medical chart containing comprehensive health information.', 'EHRs contain patient medical history, diagnoses, medications, treatment plans, immunizations, allergies, radiology images, and laboratory test results. Unlike paper records, EHRs can be shared across healthcare settings, improving care coordination and patient safety. Certified EHRs meet standards for meaningful use/promoting interoperability, qualifying providers for CMS incentives and avoiding penalties. EHRs integrate with practice management systems for billing, scheduling, and RCM. Features include: computerized provider order entry (CPOE), clinical decision support, e-prescribing, patient portals, quality reporting, and population health management. EHR adoption is mandated for many providers participating in federal programs.', 'A primary care practice uses an EHR system that allows the physician to review patient history, view lab results from external facilities, prescribe medications electronically, document encounters with structured templates, and automatically capture charges for billing. The patient can access their records, test results, and communicate with providers through a patient portal integrated with the EHR.', 'EHRs improve clinical care quality, patient safety, and care coordination while enabling revenue cycle benefits through better documentation, charge capture, and coding accuracy. However, poor EHR documentation can create compliance risks. EHR-PM integration is essential for efficient workflows. EHR implementation and optimization require significant investment but are necessary for modern healthcare delivery and value-based care programs.', 'Healthcare IT', ARRAY['Practice Management System', 'Meaningful Use', 'Charge Capture', 'Clinical Documentation']),

('Clearinghouse', 'An entity that receives and processes electronic healthcare transactions, translating them into formats required by payers.', 'Clearinghouses serve as intermediaries between providers and payers, performing several functions: format translation (converting claims to payer-specific formats), validation (checking claims for errors before submission), routing (sending claims to appropriate payers), status tracking (monitoring claim status), and remittance processing (handling ERA files). Clearinghouses are required to be HIPAA compliant and are considered business associates. They typically charge per transaction (per claim submitted). Major clearinghouses include Change Healthcare, Availity, and others. Clearinghouses provide value by: reducing claim errors, enabling electronic submission to hundreds of payers, providing real-time claim status, and simplifying the submission process.', 'A medical practice submits all claims through a clearinghouse. When the billing staff submits 50 claims, the clearinghouse: (1) Validates each claim for formatting errors, (2) Checks for common rejection reasons, (3) Converts claims to each payer''s specific format requirements, (4) Transmits claims electronically to multiple different payers, (5) Provides confirmation of receipt, (6) Monitors claim status and provides updates. The clearinghouse charges the practice $0.50 per claim.', 'Clearinghouses dramatically reduce claim rejections and simplify multi-payer submission. Direct submission to payers requires understanding each payer''s unique format requirements - clearinghouses eliminate this complexity. Real-time eligibility checking and claim status features reduce administrative burden. However, clearinghouse fees add up, and some practices with a single dominant payer may benefit from direct submission. Most practices find clearinghouse value outweighs costs.', 'Healthcare IT', ARRAY['Claim Submission', 'ERA', 'Claim Rejection', 'EDI']),

('Modifier 25', 'A CPT modifier indicating a significant, separately identifiable evaluation and management service on the same day as another procedure.', 'Modifier 25 is appended to E/M codes when a separately identifiable E/M service is performed on the same day as a minor procedure. The E/M service must be above and beyond the usual pre- and post-procedure care. Documentation must clearly show the separate nature of the E/M service - distinct presenting problems, separate history and exam elements, or significant separately identifiable decision-making. Modifier 25 is one of the most frequently used and audited modifiers. Common audit triggers: overuse (using on every procedure day), lack of documentation supporting separate service, or using for minimal services. To support modifier 25, documentation should use separate paragraphs or sections for the E/M and procedure.', 'A patient presents for a scheduled minor skin lesion removal (CPT 11200). During the visit, the patient also reports new onset of chest pain and shortness of breath. The physician performs a complete cardiovascular evaluation, orders an EKG, and determines the patient needs referral to cardiology. The billing would include: 11200 for the lesion removal, and 99213-25 (or appropriate E/M level) for the separate cardiovascular evaluation.', 'Proper use of modifier 25 captures legitimate E/M services that would otherwise go unreimbursed. However, inappropriate overuse triggers audits and creates compliance risk. Many practices either overuse modifier 25 (leading to audit risk) or underuse it (losing revenue). Clear documentation standards and regular provider education are essential. Modifier 25 denials require strong documentation in appeals to demonstrate the separate nature of services.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['CPT Code', 'Modifier', 'Evaluation and Management', 'Bundling']),

('National Provider Identifier (NPI)', 'A unique 10-digit identification number assigned to healthcare providers by CMS.', 'NPIs are required for all HIPAA-covered healthcare providers and are used on all electronic transactions, including claims, eligibility inquiries, and referrals. There are two types: Type 1 (individual providers like physicians, nurses, therapists) and Type 2 (organizational providers like hospitals, clinics, group practices). NPIs are permanent and do not change if a provider changes specialties, locations, or states. Providers must apply for NPIs through NPPES (National Plan and Provider Enumeration System). Using incorrect or missing NPIs is a common cause of claim rejections. Practices must ensure all rendering, referring, and billing provider NPIs are accurate and up to date on claims.', 'Dr. Smith''s individual NPI (Type 1) is 1234567890. When Dr. Smith joins ABC Medical Group, the practice''s organizational NPI (Type 2) is 9876543210. On claims, the billing provider NPI is the group''s (9876543210) and the rendering provider NPI is Dr. Smith''s individual NPI (1234567890). If the claim is missing or has an incorrect rendering NPI, it will be rejected by the payer.', 'Accurate NPI usage is essential for clean claims and provider credentialing. NPI errors are a top rejection reason. Providers must update their NPI information in NPPES when practice information changes. Taxonomy codes linked to NPIs must accurately reflect the provider''s specialty. Using another provider''s NPI (even within the same practice) can constitute fraud if done knowingly to obtain payment.', 'Billing Process', ARRAY['Credentialing', 'Claim Rejection', 'NPPES', 'Rendering Provider']),

('Bundling', 'When separate procedure codes are combined into a single, comprehensive code for billing purposes.', 'Bundling occurs when multiple procedure codes are billed together but payer edits combine them into one code based on coding guidelines or payer policies. The most common bundling edits come from: NCCI (National Correct Coding Initiative) edits, CCI (Correct Coding Initiative) edits, and payer-specific bundling rules. Bundling is appropriate when procedures are integral to each other, represent different components of a comprehensive service, or are performed through the same surgical approach. Unbundling (billing separately for services that should be bundled) is considered fraudulent if done intentionally. Modifier 59 or X-modifiers can override bundling edits when procedures are truly distinct and separate.', 'A surgeon performs a tonsillectomy (CPT 42820) and adenoidectomy (CPT 42830) during the same operative session. Instead of billing both codes separately, the correct code is CPT 42821 (tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy, age under 12), which bundles both procedures. If the surgeon bills both 42820 and 42830, the claim will be denied for incorrect bundling, or one procedure will be bundled (not separately reimbursed).', 'Understanding bundling rules prevents claim denials and compliance issues. Intentional unbundling to increase reimbursement is fraud and can result in severe penalties. However, appropriate use of modifiers can enable separate payment when procedures are distinct. Practices should use NCCI edit-checking software and train coders on bundling rules. Some bundling is controversial, and legitimate separate procedures may be bundled incorrectly by payers, requiring appeals with documentation.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['NCCI Edits', 'Modifier 59', 'Unbundling', 'CPT Code']),

('Pre-Authorization', 'Approval from an insurance company obtained before services are provided, confirming coverage.', 'Pre-authorization (also called prior authorization or pre-certification) is a utilization management requirement where payers review medical necessity before services are rendered. Services commonly requiring pre-auth include: surgeries, advanced imaging (MRI/CT), specialty medications, certain DME, specialist consultations, and high-cost procedures. The process typically requires submitting: clinical documentation, diagnosis information, planned procedure details, and medical necessity justification. Pre-auth determinations specify: approved services, number of units/visits, valid date range, and authorization reference number. The authorization number must be included on claims. Some authorizations have visit or unit limits requiring tracking. Emergency services typically have post-service authorization processes.', 'A patient needs a shoulder MRI. Before scheduling, the provider''s office: (1) Verifies that the patient''s insurance requires MRI pre-authorization, (2) Submits a pre-auth request with clinical notes showing failed conservative treatment and specific findings, (3) Receives authorization within 3 business days, (4) Schedules the MRI within the authorization valid dates, (5) Includes the authorization number on the claim submission.', 'Obtaining required pre-authorizations prevents claim denials and financial losses. Services provided without required authorization are often not covered, creating write-offs and patient billing disputes. Authorization requirements vary widely by payer and plan, requiring staff to verify requirements for each patient. Tracking authorization expiration dates and approved limits prevents claim denials. Many practices struggle with authorization processes, leading to significant denied claims that could be prevented.', 'Insurance Terms', ARRAY['Authorization', 'Medical Necessity', 'Utilization Management', 'Claim Denial']),

('Medicare', 'Federal health insurance program primarily for people 65 and older, plus certain disabled individuals.', 'Medicare has four parts: Part A (hospital insurance, covers inpatient care), Part B (medical insurance, covers physician services and outpatient care), Part C (Medicare Advantage, private insurance alternative offering Parts A and B benefits), and Part D (prescription drug coverage). Medicare is the largest payer in the U.S. and sets payment standards often adopted by other payers. Medicare pays using fee schedules (physician fee schedule for Part B, IPPS for hospital inpatient, OPPS for hospital outpatient). Medicare has specific billing rules, documentation requirements, and compliance regulations. Medicare patients may have secondary insurance (Medigap, employer coverage, Medicaid). Medicare processes claims through regional MACs (Medicare Administrative Contractors).', 'A 68-year-old patient on Medicare Part B visits their doctor (covered under Part B). They also have a Medigap supplemental plan. After the visit, Medicare is billed first as primary insurance. Medicare pays 80% of the approved amount after the annual deductible is met. The claim is then automatically crossed over to the Medigap plan, which typically covers the 20% coinsurance, leaving the patient with little or no out-of-pocket cost.', 'Medicare is often the largest payer for most practices, making Medicare compliance and billing expertise critical. Medicare payment rates often set the benchmark for other payers. Medicare has extensive documentation requirements and actively audits providers. Medicare fraud and abuse enforcement is aggressive through RAC, ZPIC, and UPIC audits. Understanding Medicare rules (like the physician fee schedule, bundling edits, and documentation requirements) is essential for proper billing and compliance.', 'Insurance Terms', ARRAY['Medicare Advantage', 'Medigap', 'Fee Schedule', 'MAC']),

('Medicaid', 'Joint federal and state health insurance program for low-income individuals and families.', 'Medicaid eligibility and benefits vary by state, as each state administers its own program within federal guidelines. Medicaid covers: pregnant women, children, parents, seniors, and people with disabilities who meet income requirements. The Affordable Care Act expanded Medicaid eligibility in participating states. Medicaid is often the lowest-paying insurance, with reimbursement rates sometimes below cost of care. Some states use managed care organizations (MCOs) for Medicaid, requiring separate contracting. Medicaid billing has specific requirements varying by state. Many Medicaid patients have other insurance (Medicare, employer coverage) with Medicaid as secondary. Medicaid billing often has specific state-level rules, forms, and prior authorization requirements different from commercial payers.', 'A 6-year-old child has Medicaid coverage through their state program. When they visit the pediatrician for a well-child check, the practice verifies the child''s active Medicaid coverage, confirms the service is covered (preventive care is typically covered at 100%), provides the service, and submits the claim to the state''s Medicaid program. Payment is typically lower than commercial insurance but no patient balance is allowed (Medicaid patients cannot be balance-billed for covered services).', 'Medicaid reimbursement is often significantly lower than Medicare or commercial insurance, affecting practice finances. However, many practices serve Medicaid populations as part of their mission. Understanding state-specific Medicaid rules is essential - billing Medicaid incorrectly can result in audits and repayment demands. Some states have mandatory managed Medicaid, requiring providers to contract with specific MCOs. Medicaid billing often requires additional documentation and has longer payment cycles than commercial insurance.', 'Insurance Terms', ARRAY['Medicare', 'Managed Care', 'MCO', 'Fee-for-Service']),

('Explanation of Payment (EOP)', 'A document showing how Medicare or other payers processed and paid claims, similar to EOB but from payer to provider.', 'EOPs (also called remittance advice or RA) are sent from payers to providers explaining claim adjudication. EOPs include: claim details, service dates, procedure codes, allowed amounts, payment amounts, adjustments, patient responsibility, and remark/adjustment codes explaining claim actions. Medicare sends EOPs through Medicare Remittance Advice (MRA) - electronic version is called ERA (835 file). EOPs are essential for payment posting, identifying denials, recognizing underpayments, and reconciling bank deposits to claims. Electronic EOPs enable automated payment posting, while paper EOPs require manual entry. Providers should review EOPs line by line to identify errors, denials requiring action, and opportunities to appeal incorrect adjudications.', 'A practice receives a Medicare EOP showing 25 claims processed. Reviewing line by line shows: 20 claims paid as expected, 2 claims denied for missing information (can be corrected and resubmitted), 2 claims paid at lower amounts than expected (require investigation), and 1 claim rejected as a duplicate. The billing staff uses this EOP to: post payments, identify the 2 correctable denials for rework, research the 2 underpayments, and investigate the duplicate rejection.', 'Careful EOP review is essential for maximizing revenue and identifying issues. Many practices post payments without thorough EOP review, missing denials, underpayments, and errors. Line-by-line EOP review can identify payer errors worth appealing. Understanding adjustment codes (CARC and RARC codes) is necessary to interpret EOPs and determine appropriate follow-up actions. EOPs should be retained for compliance and audit purposes.', 'Claims & Denials', ARRAY['ERA', 'EOB', 'Remittance Advice', 'Payment Posting']);

