-- Additional essential terms
INSERT INTO glossary_terms (term, definition, detailed_explanation, example, why_it_matters, category, related_terms) VALUES
('Encounter Form', 'A paper or electronic form listing common diagnosis and procedure codes used during patient encounters for charge capture.', 'Also called a superbill or fee ticket, encounter forms facilitate accurate charge capture by providing providers and staff with commonly used codes specific to their specialty. Forms typically include: patient demographics section, common CPT codes with descriptions, common ICD-10 codes, modifier options, and spaces for additional notes. Paper forms are marked during or after the encounter and sent to billing. Electronic forms are built into EHRs for real-time charge capture. Well-designed encounter forms improve coding accuracy, reduce missed charges, and speed billing processes. Forms should be updated annually when CPT and ICD codes change and reviewed periodically to add/remove codes based on usage patterns.', 'A family medicine practice creates an encounter form with the most common office visit codes (99202-99215), common diagnoses (hypertension, diabetes, upper respiratory infections), preventive care codes (99381-99397), and common procedures (injections, simple laceration repairs). When a provider sees a patient, they check the appropriate boxes, which are then entered into the billing system or automatically captured if using an electronic form.', 'Proper encounter form design directly impacts charge capture accuracy and completeness. Poor or outdated forms lead to missed charges, incorrect coding, and delayed billing. Electronic encounter forms integrated with EHRs enable real-time charge capture and reduce transcription errors. Encounter forms should make proper coding easy while discouraging "checkbox medicine" where inappropriate codes are selected for convenience rather than accuracy.', 'Billing Process', ARRAY['Charge Capture', 'CPT Code', 'ICD-10 Code', 'Superbill']),

('Fee Schedule', 'A complete listing of fees or charges for medical services provided by a healthcare facility or provider.', 'Fee schedules establish the prices practices charge for all services before any payer adjustments. Effective fee schedules are set above payer contracted rates to avoid leaving money on the table. Common approaches: charge a consistent percentage above Medicare (e.g., 150% of Medicare), use market-based pricing from regional data, or maintain historical charges with annual updates. Fee schedules should be reviewed annually and updated for: new codes, deleted codes, relative value changes, and market positioning. All payers see the same full fee schedule, but contracted rates (allowed amounts) vary by payer. For out-of-network claims, charges may influence payment if payers use UCR methodologies. Consistent fee schedules across all payers are required - differential pricing is prohibited by most payer contracts.', 'A practice sets its fee schedule at 180% of Medicare rates. Medicare''s rate for CPT 99214 is $110, so the practice charges $198. When billing: Medicare pays $110 (contracted rate), the practice takes an $88 adjustment. A commercial payer contracted at $145 pays that amount, with a $53 adjustment. An out-of-network payer without a contract might pay based on the $198 charge or their UCR determination.', 'Fee schedules impact revenue when new payers are contracted or for out-of-network services. Charges set too low mean negotiated rates may also be lower, directly reducing revenue. However, very high charges create large adjustment amounts that can mislead financial analysis. Fee schedule maintenance is often neglected, but annual reviews ensure practices maximize revenue opportunities. Out-of-network pricing strategies require thoughtful fee schedule management.', 'Financial Terms', ARRAY['Allowed Amount', 'Adjustment', 'UCR', 'Contracted Rate']),

('Upcoding', 'The practice of billing a higher-level service code than what was actually provided or documented.', 'Upcoding is a form of fraud where providers intentionally bill higher-level codes to receive increased reimbursement. Examples: billing a 99215 when documentation supports only 99213, billing a complex procedure when a simple version was performed, or adding units/quantities beyond what was provided. Upcoding violates the False Claims Act and can result in: payment recoupment, civil monetary penalties, criminal prosecution, exclusion from federal programs, and loss of medical license. Unintentional upcoding (due to coding errors or misunderstanding) is still problematic and can trigger audits. Conversely, downcoding (billing lower than documented) costs practices revenue but isn''t fraudulent. Proper training, documentation requirements, and internal audits prevent upcoding.', 'A provider performs a straightforward office visit with established patient addressing one stable chronic condition (appropriate code: 99213). The provider or coder bills 99215 (highest level E/M) to receive $180 instead of $110. If done knowingly and repeatedly, this constitutes upcoding fraud. If audited, the provider would face repayment demands plus penalties, and potential criminal prosecution if deemed intentional fraud.', 'Upcoding is a serious compliance risk that can destroy careers and practices. Even unintentional patterns of upcoding trigger audits, requiring practices to repay overpayments with interest and potential penalties. Documentation must support the level billed - when in doubt, bill conservatively. Regular internal audits identify coding patterns that may appear like upcoding to external auditors. Compliance training emphasizes: "code what''s documented, document what''s done."', 'Compliance & Regulations', ARRAY['Compliance', 'Fraud and Abuse', 'False Claims Act', 'Documentation']),

('Downcoding', 'When a payer reduces a claim to a lower-level code or service than what the provider billed.', 'Downcoding by payers occurs for several reasons: insufficient documentation, failure to meet criteria for billed level, bundling edits, or payer policy disagreements. Downcoding reduces reimbursement below what the provider expected. Common examples: billing 99215 but paid at 99214 level due to documentation not supporting highest level, billing bilateral procedure but paid as unilateral, or complex service paid at simple level. Downcoding can be appropriate (when provider overcoded) or inappropriate (when documentation supports billed level but payer disagrees). Inappropriate downcoding should be appealed with supporting documentation. Provider-initiated downcoding (billing lower than documentation supports) is not fraudulent but costs revenue and should be minimized through proper training.', 'A provider documents and bills CPT 99215 (highest complexity established patient visit) but the payer downcodes and pays at 99214 level, reducing payment from $180 to $140. On review, the provider finds documentation fully supports 99215 with high complexity medical decision-making and 40+ minutes total time. The provider appeals with documentation highlighting the elements supporting 99215, and the payer overturns the downcoding and pays the additional $40.', 'Downcoding by payers reduces practice revenue and should be monitored. If specific codes are routinely downcoded, either: documentation needs improvement, providers are overcoding, or payer policies require appeals. Tracking downcoding patterns by code and payer identifies targets for corrective action. Provider-initiated downcoding (billing conservatively) costs practices significant revenue - studies show many practices lose 2-5% of potential revenue due to conservative coding when documentation supports higher levels.', 'Medical Coding', ARRAY['Upcoding', 'Documentation', 'Appeal Process', 'Medical Decision Making']);

